Deceased","1335–1379":"1335–1379","1360–1429":"1360–1429","1356–Male":"1356–Deceased","1321–Female":"1321–Deceased","1379":"1379","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1321":"1321","about 1359":"about 1359","1360":"1360","1429":"1429","Linlithgowshire, Scotland":"Linlithgowshire, Scotland","Melville, Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland":"Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Caldwell, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Caldwell, Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cumin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Muslim (mainly Somalia and Bangladesh, also Ghana): from a personal name based on Arabic <i>mu’min</i> ‘believer (in Islam), pious person’. <i>Al-Mu’min</i> ‘the Believer’ is an attribute of Allah (Koran 59:23). It is also the title of the 40th sura of the Koran. Compare   Momin   and   Memon  . — Note: Since Somalis traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, this name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."],"variants":[{"name":"Momin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Karim, Akbar, Zulfiqar, Amirali, Sadruddin, Nasir, Salim, Sultan, Ahmed, Amir, Inayat, Nizar.","Muslim (Indian subcontinent): variant of   Mumin  ."]},{"name":"Memon","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Abdul, Mohammed, Mohammad, Altaf, Haji, Iqbal, Ahmed, Ali, Ghulam, Haroon, Liaquat, Muhammad.","Pakistani and Indian (Gujarat): Muslim name, from an altered form of Arabic <i>muʿmin</i> ‘believer’ (see   Mumin  )."]},{"name":"Muminovic","meanings":["Bosniak (<b>Muminović</b>): patronymic from the Muslim personal name   Mumin  ."]}]},{"name":"Isobel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isobel Cumin was born in 1321, in Linlithgowshire, Scotland. She married John Melville Of Fife about 1359, in Fife, Scotland. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Caldwell, Ayrshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1321–":"1321–Surnud","1335–1379":"1335–1379","1360–1429":"1360–1429","1356–Male":"1356–Surnud","1321–Female":"1321–Surnud","1379":"1379","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1321":"1321","about 1359":"umbes 1359","1360":"1360","1429":"1429","Linlithgowshire, Scotland":"Linlithgowshire, Scotland","Melville, Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland":"Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Caldwell, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Caldwell, Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1321–":"1321–Kuollut","1335–1379":"1335–1379","1360–1429":"1360–1429","1356–Male":"1356–Kuollut","1321–Female":"1321–Kuollut","1379":"1379","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1321":"1321","about 1359":"noin 1359","1360":"1360","1429":"1429","Linlithgowshire, Scotland":"Linlithgowshire, Scotland","Melville, Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland":"Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland","Fife, Scotland":"Fife, Scotland","Caldwell, Ayrshire, Scotland":"Caldwell, Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fr":{"1321–":"1321–Décédée","1335–1379":"1335–1379","1360–1429":"1360–1429","1356–Male":"1356–Décédé","1321–Female":"1321–Décédée","1379":"1379","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1321":"1321","about 1359":"environ 1359","1360":"1360","1429":"1429","Linlithgowshire, Scotland":"Linlithgowshire, Écosse","Melville, Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland":"Lasswade, Midl